48
00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:54.320
to think about

49
00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:58.820
the selective vulnerabilities of pancreatic cancer cells as they

50
00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:02.400
migrate from the primary site to metastatic sites,

51
00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:03.980
mostly the liver and the lungs.

52
00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.420
Because this is about secreted factors, I'm going to tell you about maybe an

53
00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:12.280
unexpected secreted factor that you may not have thought about in the past.

54
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:13.200
So,

55
00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:15.160
just for

56
00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:20.460
background, I know many of you here know a lot about pancreatic cancer.

57
00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:23.320
For those of you who may not, these are some of the key features.

58
00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:25.500
I won't go through all the details of this.

59
00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:29.040
I'll highlight some excellent reviews that

60
00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:32.920
have been published by colleagues in the field.

61
00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.220
What I'll focus on primarily today has been what we study

62
00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:42.150
in my lab, which is the role of nutrient

63
00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:45.970
scavenging pathways that I'll describe in a little bit more detail, as well as, as

64
00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:49.740
I mentioned, their role during metastatic spread throughout the

65
00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:50.040
body.

66
00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:54.720
So we study these pathways called autophagy,

67
00:03:54.840 --> 00:03:58.450
macropinocytosis, which we broadly refer to as nutrient scavenging

68
00:03:58.540 --> 00:04:02.220
pathways. These are all upregulated in pancreatic ductal

69
00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:06.180
adenocarcinoma, which is the cancer of the pancreas that we focus on in the

70
00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:08.040
lab. It's the most aggressive variant

71
00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:12.680
of pancreas cancer. There's an organ

72
00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:16.519
site-specific session that's at 12:30 today, so I encourage you all to go

73
00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:19.640
if you're interested in this disease and want to learn more.

74
00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:24.280
For the purposes of today, though, I want to highlight the fact that these pathways

75
00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:28.260
are upregulated. This is work done by Alec Kimmelman and several others showing

76
00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:29.730
that a process called autophagy is

77
00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:34.180
constitutively active. This is a process whereby you capture

78
00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:37.980
intracellular material, package it into a double membrane vesicle, and then bring

79
00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:39.620
it to the lysosome for degradation.

80
00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:42.540
Cosimo Commisso, Dafna Bar-Sagi

81
00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:46.950
showed that another scavenging pathway called macropinocytosis is also

82
00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:50.540
upregulated. Captures extracellular components such as

83
00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:54.390
lipids and proteins, and again, packages them, brings it to the lysosome for

84
00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:58.240
degradation. And as you would expect, PDAC cells upregulate lysosomal

85
00:04:58.300 --> 00:04:59.440
biogenesis to

86
00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:04.060
contend with this increased flux of traffic that comes to the

87
00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:05.300
lysosome to be degraded.

88
00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:06.340
So,

89
00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:12.110
some of you may know a lot about the lysosome, some of you may not, but this is a

90
00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:16.020
fascinating organelle that we've spent a lot of our time thinking about in more

91
00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:19.980
detail, primarily because it is a central degradative and metabolic

92
00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:23.660
hub within the cell. Again, it's about 15-fold upregulated.

93
00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:27.620
It's biogenesis in PDAC, and it serves a number of important

94
00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:31.620
roles. It has enzymes within its lumen that's responsible for

95
00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:34.040
breakdown of all macromolecules within a cell.

96
00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:36.300
Proteins, lipids, nucleic acids, sugars.

97
00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:40.700
It has sensors, metabolic sensors that can detect the amount of

98
00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:44.060
luminal nutrients as well as cytoplasmic nutrients.

99
00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:48.000
It has transporters that can exchange these degradation products back with the

100
00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:51.280
cell to fuel bioenergetic and biosynthetic processes.

101
00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:55.800
And signal transducers like the mammalian target or mechanistic

102
00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:59.760
target of rapamycin, an important growth regulator that localizes

103
00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:02.040
to the lysosome in order to be activated and then

104
00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:06.200
transmits signals, proliferative signals from

105
00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:09.988
the lysosomal membrane.So when I started my lab many years ago

106
00:06:10.048 --> 00:06:13.988
now, we were interested in understanding how is the lysosome different in

107
00:06:14.048 --> 00:06:15.308
cancer cells versus

108
00:06:16.588 --> 00:06:20.488
normal cells. And to do this, we used a technique developed in David Sabatini's

109
00:06:20.528 --> 00:06:24.278
lab that allows us to immunoisolate intact lysosomes from

110
00:06:24.308 --> 00:06:27.348
cells that are then amenable to mass spec-based analysis.

111
00:06:27.528 --> 00:06:31.318
I won't go through the details here, but just to say that we can compare

112
00:06:31.328 --> 00:06:34.578
by using proteomics all the proteins that

113
00:06:34.688 --> 00:06:38.498
are captured within lysosomes or the resident proteins that are

114
00:06:38.608 --> 00:06:42.008
specific to this organelle isolated from a tumor cell

115
00:06:42.068 --> 00:06:45.708
versus the same organelle isolated from a non-tumor cell.

116
00:06:46.148 --> 00:06:50.068
So everything on the right-hand side of this volcano plot is proteins

117
00:06:50.128 --> 00:06:53.888
enriched in PDAC lysosomes. Everything on the left are proteins enriched in normal

118
00:06:53.928 --> 00:06:57.848
lysosomes. They fall into two categories, cargoes that are brought from

119
00:06:57.888 --> 00:07:01.878
elsewhere in the cell or outside the cell to be degraded, or

120
00:07:02.028 --> 00:07:05.468
resident proteins that are intrinsic to the lysosome, like those

121
00:07:05.508 --> 00:07:07.458
transporters, like enzymes and so on.

122
00:07:08.368 --> 00:07:11.608
And you can tell from this plot alone that there's a huge difference.

123
00:07:11.628 --> 00:07:15.508
There's things that are very much unique to the cancer context and things that are

124
00:07:15.568 --> 00:07:16.848
unique to the normal context.

125
00:07:17.888 --> 00:07:21.308
Over the years, we've used this technique to understand a lot about how the

126
00:07:21.348 --> 00:07:25.228
lysosome contributes to all these different processes within PDAC

127
00:07:25.308 --> 00:07:28.808
cells, from resistance to therapy, selective degradation of

128
00:07:28.908 --> 00:07:32.778
certain cargoes versus others. And what I want to tell you about

129
00:07:32.808 --> 00:07:36.678
today is related a little bit more to metabolism and

130
00:07:36.688 --> 00:07:40.118
metastasis and how we've been able to take this

131
00:07:40.148 --> 00:07:44.108
technique from isolating lysosomes from 2D cultured cells, which is what we

132
00:07:44.188 --> 00:07:48.048
did traditionally, and translating this to

133
00:07:48.188 --> 00:07:52.168
in vivo tumors. So while there's a lot we can learn by

134
00:07:52.268 --> 00:07:55.868
isolating lysosomes and profiling their content from cells cultured in

135
00:07:55.968 --> 00:07:59.808
2D, we recognize that's not representative of how these tumors grow

136
00:07:59.908 --> 00:08:03.868
in our bodies, right? So Grace Hernandez, who's a graduate student

137
00:08:03.888 --> 00:08:06.988
in my lab, really took on this project, which is very challenging.

138
00:08:07.388 --> 00:08:10.638
How do you go about purifying lysosomes from a tumor growing

139
00:08:10.668 --> 00:08:14.508
within a living organism and specifically from the tumor

140
00:08:14.548 --> 00:08:18.408
epithelia? So what we did as a simple way is

141
00:08:18.467 --> 00:08:22.248
to engineer this tag into mouse PDAC

142
00:08:22.268 --> 00:08:26.168
lines, and then we transplanted them either into the

143
00:08:26.208 --> 00:08:30.148
pancreas. And in the course of this process, Grace

144
00:08:30.208 --> 00:08:34.048
also wanted to understand an important question about how perhaps the lysosome

145
00:08:34.228 --> 00:08:37.518
helps cells to adapt once they're growing into these two different

146
00:08:37.548 --> 00:08:40.249
metastatic sites, the liver and the lung.

147
00:08:40.288 --> 00:08:44.188
So what she did here was to take these KPCL, because it expresses the tag,

148
00:08:44.568 --> 00:08:48.388
or KPC with no tag, inject them orthotopic to

149
00:08:48.428 --> 00:08:52.358
seed the pancreas, intra-splenically to seed the liver, or via tail vein to

150
00:08:52.388 --> 00:08:56.268
seed the lung. She then customized techniques to be able to purify lysosomes

151
00:08:56.308 --> 00:08:59.228
from tumors growing in each of these three different locations.

152
00:08:59.668 --> 00:09:03.368
The proteomics was done in collaboration with Joe Mankus at Dana-Farber.

153
00:09:03.388 --> 00:09:07.208
And this is just to show you the purity of these in vivo LysoIPs that we're now

154
00:09:07.248 --> 00:09:10.748
doing. So here you can see cells expressing the lysotag.

155
00:09:11.168 --> 00:09:14.708
You get purification of lysosome-specific proteins, but all

156
00:09:14.788 --> 00:09:18.548
other organelle markers of other organelles are not there because they get

157
00:09:18.588 --> 00:09:22.338
washed away in the flow-through. Whereas the tumors that don't have the

158
00:09:22.408 --> 00:09:24.408
tag, you really don't purify anything at all.

159
00:09:26.128 --> 00:09:29.188
And then we did the mass spec with Joe. So this is what it looks like.

160
00:09:29.608 --> 00:09:32.808
Tumors isolated from the pancreas, liver, and lung.

161
00:09:32.908 --> 00:09:36.408
We then purify the lysosomes, and you can see a really nice

162
00:09:36.418 --> 00:09:39.268
enrichment of luminal hydrolases.

163
00:09:39.308 --> 00:09:41.188
That tells us the lysosomes are intact.

164
00:09:42.328 --> 00:09:46.108
Tumors that don't have the lysotag, you notice this is pretty clean, so we're not

165
00:09:46.328 --> 00:09:48.208
purifying really anything because there's no tag.

166
00:09:48.928 --> 00:09:51.168
And we can do this successively from all three sites.

167
00:09:52.048 --> 00:09:55.668
From here, we then can start to understand what's common and

168
00:09:55.688 --> 00:09:59.648
unique to the cargoes that are targeted to the lysosome for degradation.

169
00:09:59.688 --> 00:10:03.528
There's a lot of things that are common, some things that are common to the

170
00:10:03.548 --> 00:10:07.368
metastatic sites, some things that are common to one metastatic site

171
00:10:07.408 --> 00:10:10.978
versus another. And I want to take you quickly through them, like some

172
00:10:11.008 --> 00:10:14.748
examples. So MHC class 1 we had shown previously was an

173
00:10:14.788 --> 00:10:17.628
enriched cargo that was targeted for degradation in PDAC.

174
00:10:17.688 --> 00:10:20.528
We can find this in in vivo tumors as well.

175
00:10:20.568 --> 00:10:24.558
We can find other processes like mitochondrial turnover are really

176
00:10:24.688 --> 00:10:28.388
unique to the lung tumors. So the lysosomes are

177
00:10:28.448 --> 00:10:31.208
turning over mitochondria much more efficiently in the lung.

178
00:10:31.288 --> 00:10:34.028
Perhaps this makes sense. This is a more oxygenated environment.

179
00:10:34.288 --> 00:10:36.188
They're more likely to have mitochondrial damage.

180
00:10:36.737 --> 00:10:39.368
And then we see other things that are unique, perhaps to the liver.

181
00:10:39.548 --> 00:10:43.068
So cholesterol transport, we published a paper on this last year,

182
00:10:43.508 --> 00:10:47.308
and then turnover of extracellular matrix and intragrins, which I'll talk

183
00:10:47.368 --> 00:10:50.668
about a little bit more later on. So Grace had to make an executive

184
00:10:50.688 --> 00:10:54.678
decision. Of all these proteins, how do you pick one thing

185
00:10:55.228 --> 00:10:58.568
and build a thesis project? Not an easy thing to do,

186
00:10:58.608 --> 00:11:02.338
but she did it. And she decided to focus not on the cargoes,

187
00:11:02.708 --> 00:11:05.908
but on the resident proteins, the lysosomal resident proteins.

188
00:11:06.508 --> 00:11:10.208
So most of them are the same. Lysosomes are lysosomes, right?

189
00:11:10.288 --> 00:11:12.508
So there's transporters, there's enzymes, and so on.

190
00:11:12.568 --> 00:11:16.558
But she noticed one lysosomal enzyme that was different, and it's called

191
00:11:16.608 --> 00:11:20.458
legumen. It's a asparaginyl endopeptidase, broadly expressed,

192
00:11:21.028 --> 00:11:24.788
well-characterized, crystal structure is known, and the substrates

193
00:11:24.968 --> 00:11:27.168
are also fairly well-characterized.

194
00:11:27.348 --> 00:11:30.348
Matrix proteins, MMPs, cathepsins, and so on.

195
00:11:31.308 --> 00:11:34.508
So we went back and looked at our tumors, and you can clearly see that--

196
00:11:35.268 --> 00:11:36.528
so I should say, sorry, going back.

197
00:11:36.998 --> 00:11:40.888
This was really down-regulated in the pancreas or de-enriched,

198
00:11:40.948 --> 00:11:43.468
but then high in the liver versus the lung.

199
00:11:43.868 --> 00:11:46.928
So that was also a really interesting aspect for us to understand.

200
00:11:47.368 --> 00:11:51.288
Why was this lysosomal enzyme being enriched in the metastatic

201
00:11:51.348 --> 00:11:53.788
lesion? So we went back and stained for legumen.

202
00:11:53.928 --> 00:11:57.508
This is in blue. What you'll notice in the tumor

203
00:11:57.568 --> 00:12:01.348
epithelia, which is here, you really don't see a lot of legumen at

204
00:12:01.428 --> 00:12:05.228
all. There's lots in the stroma. These macrophages express it, fibroblasts

205
00:12:05.288 --> 00:12:08.808
express it, but the tumor epithelia does not when it's growing in the

206
00:12:08.848 --> 00:12:12.408
pancreas. These same cells, when transplanted in the

207
00:12:12.528 --> 00:12:15.112
liver, thoughupregulate legumen.

208
00:12:15.192 --> 00:12:18.952
Now you can see there's a lot of legumen in the tumor epithelia, as well as in the

209
00:12:18.992 --> 00:12:22.822
surrounding tumor. Now, if we just did a whole cell lysate of the tumor, we'd never

210
00:12:22.932 --> 00:12:26.552
see this difference because the external tumor

211
00:12:27.032 --> 00:12:28.732
extrinsic legumen is very high.

212
00:12:30.012 --> 00:12:33.852
So we also looked at patient PDAC. So this is primary PDAC on the

213
00:12:33.912 --> 00:12:35.932
top, liver metastasis on the bottom.

214
00:12:35.952 --> 00:12:39.742
And again, you see very high levels of legumen, much higher in the

215
00:12:39.932 --> 00:12:42.012
liver mets relative to the primary.

216
00:12:43.992 --> 00:12:46.171
So what does this mean? Is this functionally important?

217
00:12:46.232 --> 00:12:48.032
So what she did was to knock out legumen

218
00:12:48.892 --> 00:12:52.872
in our KPC lines, no defect in

219
00:12:53.152 --> 00:12:56.552
vitro proliferation. And then what she did was to

220
00:12:56.612 --> 00:13:00.172
orthotopically transplant them back into the pancreas or via

221
00:13:00.212 --> 00:13:03.892
intrasplenic injection into the liver. And she noticed something really striking.

222
00:13:04.712 --> 00:13:08.592
So loss of legumen doesn't lead to any change in the ability of the

223
00:13:08.632 --> 00:13:10.332
tumors to grow in the pancreas.

224
00:13:11.172 --> 00:13:15.152
Tumor weights are the same. But those same cells injected back into the

225
00:13:15.212 --> 00:13:19.172
liver, what she noticed is their ability to grow was severely compromised.

226
00:13:19.212 --> 00:13:23.111
So this is overall tumor weight, and this is what the histology looks like.

227
00:13:23.172 --> 00:13:25.112
So normally they grow really fine.

228
00:13:25.152 --> 00:13:28.832
They grow well in the pancreas as well, but the same cells transplanted to grow in

229
00:13:28.872 --> 00:13:31.032
the liver have a compromised ability to grow.

230
00:13:31.992 --> 00:13:35.952
So this suggested that a lysosomal enzyme shows selective

231
00:13:36.012 --> 00:13:39.952
dependency, is selectively required for growth in the liver, but not in

232
00:13:39.992 --> 00:13:40.672
the pancreas.

233
00:13:41.832 --> 00:13:44.772
So what happened? So it's a lysosomal enzyme.

234
00:13:44.812 --> 00:13:47.452
We looked at the lysosomal morphology to begin with.

235
00:13:47.592 --> 00:13:51.002
Usually when you lose one of these enzymes, you start to see lysosomal defects,

236
00:13:51.052 --> 00:13:54.652
which is characterized by an increase in lysosomal size as things start to

237
00:13:54.672 --> 00:13:57.952
accumulate and not get digested. And you can see that here

238
00:13:57.992 --> 00:14:01.702
compared to the control, our lysosomes start to look big and

239
00:14:01.732 --> 00:14:02.142
bloated.

240
00:14:03.172 --> 00:14:07.052
We also know what legumen does. So I'm going to take you through this a little

241
00:14:07.092 --> 00:14:10.072
slowly. So these are lysosomal cathepsins.

242
00:14:10.112 --> 00:14:13.952
These are other proteases that are also present within the lysosome.

243
00:14:14.352 --> 00:14:17.912
And what legumen's role is, is to be able to facilitate their

244
00:14:17.972 --> 00:14:21.432
maturation from this single chain form to a two chain form.

245
00:14:21.492 --> 00:14:22.292
It removes a

246
00:14:24.232 --> 00:14:27.492
small peptide, so it runs at a lower molecular weight.

247
00:14:28.052 --> 00:14:31.672
And this is thought to be the most mature form of cathepsins.

248
00:14:31.752 --> 00:14:35.292
Now, cathepsins are responsible for digestion of

249
00:14:35.392 --> 00:14:38.192
proteins that are brought to the lysosome for degradation.

250
00:14:38.772 --> 00:14:41.432
So this is what it looks like on a western blot.

251
00:14:41.512 --> 00:14:44.572
So normally this is the pro form of cathepsin L.

252
00:14:44.772 --> 00:14:44.932
It's

253
00:14:45.812 --> 00:14:48.932
matured into this two chain form. So this version here.

254
00:14:49.432 --> 00:14:52.872
If you lose legumen, you see loss of this

255
00:14:52.892 --> 00:14:56.632
maturation process and accumulation of this intermediate single

256
00:14:56.672 --> 00:15:00.592
chain form. So that's one of the main roles of legumen in the lysosome

257
00:15:00.632 --> 00:15:04.552
is to not only digest its own substrates, but several of its

258
00:15:04.572 --> 00:15:06.492
substrates are these cathepsins.

259
00:15:07.592 --> 00:15:10.132
So this is dependent on legumen activity.

260
00:15:10.372 --> 00:15:10.732
Again,

261
00:15:11.672 --> 00:15:13.572
this is the mature form of cathepsin.

262
00:15:13.612 --> 00:15:17.172
If you lose it, you get accumulation of this single chain form.

263
00:15:17.582 --> 00:15:21.192
In the knockout cells, if we put back wild type, you can see it

264
00:15:21.292 --> 00:15:25.192
rescues the phenotype. If you put two catalytically dead variants, you can see

265
00:15:25.212 --> 00:15:27.472
that now we don't rescue the phenotype.

266
00:15:27.512 --> 00:15:31.392
So this is very much dependent on legumen catalytic activity. Okay.

267
00:15:32.672 --> 00:15:36.262
Cathepsin activity is reduced. It's not completely blocked because

268
00:15:36.332 --> 00:15:39.792
the single chain form still retains some activity.

269
00:15:39.832 --> 00:15:43.072
What's thought is that the substrate selectivity starts to change.

270
00:15:43.852 --> 00:15:47.712
So this is where it gets very interesting and where secretion becomes

271
00:15:47.772 --> 00:15:49.612
interesting, as is the theme of this session.

272
00:15:50.332 --> 00:15:54.292
So what's known is that when you have lysosomal defects,

273
00:15:54.332 --> 00:15:57.932
such as increases in size, as well as the accumulation of

274
00:15:57.972 --> 00:16:01.552
immature cathepsins, in order to sustain

275
00:16:01.612 --> 00:16:05.252
viability of the cells and to start to get rid of all this accumulated material

276
00:16:05.292 --> 00:16:09.092
that's not being digested properly, the lysosomes can undergo a process called

277
00:16:09.152 --> 00:16:13.092
exocytosis. They fuse with the membrane and then release all of their

278
00:16:13.132 --> 00:16:17.032
material out into the extracellular space, including these cathepsins and

279
00:16:17.072 --> 00:16:17.832
hydrolases.

280
00:16:19.112 --> 00:16:20.732
So we wanted to see whether this was happening.

281
00:16:20.852 --> 00:16:24.792
So we took isogenic lines of primary PDAC and the matched liver met

282
00:16:24.802 --> 00:16:28.772
that we isolated from a mouse, a genetically engineered mouse that develops

283
00:16:28.832 --> 00:16:32.491
PDAC spontaneously. And then we took the supernatant of these

284
00:16:32.512 --> 00:16:35.792
cells and then performed a western blot for cathepsin L.

285
00:16:36.332 --> 00:16:40.212
So this is the single chain form because the mature form never

286
00:16:40.252 --> 00:16:43.072
gets secreted. It's only the single chain form that does.

287
00:16:43.712 --> 00:16:47.532
You'll notice that in the primary, we really don't see much single

288
00:16:47.612 --> 00:16:51.592
chain being secreted at all. In the liver met, it's even

289
00:16:51.652 --> 00:16:55.612
less. But if you lose cathepsin, lose legumen,

290
00:16:55.752 --> 00:16:59.652
and you accumulate this single chain form, this intermediate

291
00:16:59.712 --> 00:17:03.412
step, now you start to see a lot more of the cathepsins being

292
00:17:03.492 --> 00:17:05.272
secreted into extracellular space.

293
00:17:05.992 --> 00:17:09.412
Now, this poses an interesting question.

294
00:17:09.572 --> 00:17:13.432
What are the substrates that this cathepsin is now starting to digest that could

295
00:17:13.472 --> 00:17:17.192
be different from what it would digest if it was natively within the lysosome

296
00:17:17.232 --> 00:17:18.652
within cells?

297
00:17:19.672 --> 00:17:23.012
And there's a lot of work that has been done by Joanna Joyce and others in the

298
00:17:23.022 --> 00:17:27.012
