491
00:26:52.826 --> 00:26:52.826
Oh.

492
00:26:52.876 --> 00:26:54.366
And my question is,

493
00:26:55.856 --> 00:26:59.696
since cathepsins can activate granzyme B-

494
00:26:59.936 --> 00:26:59.986
Yeah

495
00:26:59.986 --> 00:27:02.106
... which is produced by CD8 T cells-

496
00:27:02.236 --> 00:27:02.516
Right

497
00:27:02.536 --> 00:27:03.076
... natural killer cells.

498
00:27:04.176 --> 00:27:07.296
So natural killer cells are enriched in the liver.

499
00:27:07.416 --> 00:27:10.416
Do you think that possibly the differences that you're seeing are due

500
00:27:10.556 --> 00:27:14.546
to cathepsin's ability to activate granzyme B from NK cells in

501
00:27:14.556 --> 00:27:18.416
the liver and induce an antitumor immune response specifically in the liver

502
00:27:18.476 --> 00:27:19.106
as opposed to the other organ?

503
00:27:19.116 --> 00:27:22.656
I'm going to give you a really short answer. We don't know. Very good point.

504
00:27:22.976 --> 00:27:23.716
Can we collaborate on this?

505
00:27:23.736 --> 00:27:24.856
Sure. Let's talk.

506
00:27:25.866 --> 00:27:26.126
I'm down.

507
00:27:26.156 --> 00:27:28.516
I'm not going to ask the question because Sashi is showing.

508
00:27:28.636 --> 00:27:28.646
Okay.

509
00:27:28.676 --> 00:27:32.386
But the person that spoke before the last person, for the

510
00:27:32.436 --> 00:27:35.156
recording, that was Ruth Shuval from the Weizmann.

511
00:27:35.196 --> 00:27:36.756
Okay. Thanks, everybody.

512
00:27:36.776 --> 00:27:40.676
Thanks, Eti. I appreciate that. All right, so next up we have Jivisha

513
00:27:40.696 --> 00:27:43.196
Bajaj from University of Rochester.

514
00:27:49.876 --> 00:27:50.196
Okay.

515
00:27:52.396 --> 00:27:56.136
I'm going to start by thanking the organizers for inviting me here.

516
00:27:56.656 --> 00:27:59.476
This is my very first AACR. I'm super excited to be here.

517
00:28:00.076 --> 00:28:02.476
And also all of you for coming to my talk.

518
00:28:03.856 --> 00:28:04.096
So

519
00:28:05.756 --> 00:28:09.636
I have nothing to disclose. My lab is primarily interested in

520
00:28:09.676 --> 00:28:13.176
acute myeloid leukemias, which are characterized by this

521
00:28:13.236 --> 00:28:16.616
accumulation of immature blast cells,

522
00:28:17.196 --> 00:28:19.596
both in the peripheral blood and in the bone marrow.

523
00:28:21.476 --> 00:28:25.236
These cancers typically arise from mutations in the hematopoietic stem

524
00:28:25.256 --> 00:28:28.576
progenitor cells. They can arise de novo or

525
00:28:28.696 --> 00:28:32.136
progress from indolent diseases such as myelodysplastic

526
00:28:32.216 --> 00:28:32.796
syndromes.

527
00:28:33.796 --> 00:28:37.696
Despite the advent of targeted therapy in the last few years, such as

528
00:28:37.716 --> 00:28:41.376
venetoclax and FLT3 ITD specific inhibitors,

529
00:28:41.896 --> 00:28:45.596
the overall survival outcomes for these diseases remain fairly

530
00:28:45.656 --> 00:28:49.636
dismal, highlighting a need to think outside the box and not

531
00:28:49.676 --> 00:28:51.716
just target the mutations themselves.

532
00:28:53.456 --> 00:28:57.216
We have been greatly inspired by the large body of work in solid

533
00:28:57.276 --> 00:29:01.256
tumors showing how important the fibroblasts and the stromal

534
00:29:01.316 --> 00:29:04.336
microenvironment can be in promoting disease progression.

535
00:29:04.856 --> 00:29:08.836
So really, my lab is focusing on how interactions with these

536
00:29:08.896 --> 00:29:12.756
non-immune stromal cells can play a role in AML

537
00:29:12.776 --> 00:29:13.396
progression.

538
00:29:15.156 --> 00:29:18.476
So we are often asked, why should someone care about the

539
00:29:18.536 --> 00:29:22.256
microenvironment in a cancer which is fluid? It's everywhere.

540
00:29:22.836 --> 00:29:26.576
It is in the blood. It's in the marrow. What really is the microenvironment?

541
00:29:28.176 --> 00:29:31.876
To answer that question, we go back and ask, where do these cancers

542
00:29:31.896 --> 00:29:34.406
arise? So a large body of literature,

543
00:29:35.016 --> 00:29:38.956
primarily driven by pioneering work from the labs

544
00:29:38.996 --> 00:29:42.896
of Sean Morrison, David Scadden, Paul Frenette, and many others,

545
00:29:43.536 --> 00:29:47.056
have shown that the non-immune stromal cell niche, such as

546
00:29:47.076 --> 00:29:50.806
mesenchymal stromal cells, the osteoblasts, as well as

547
00:29:50.836 --> 00:29:54.636
endothelial cells, provide signals and support for the most

548
00:29:54.656 --> 00:29:56.306
primitive hematopoietic stem cells.

549
00:29:56.916 --> 00:30:00.456
So this gives us some rationale for actually studying whether the same

550
00:30:00.496 --> 00:30:03.816
cells can now support the leukemia cells,

551
00:30:04.836 --> 00:30:08.656
and at least in the beginning, when they're actually in this niche, which is also

552
00:30:08.696 --> 00:30:11.496
occupied by the normal, non-mutant cells.

553
00:30:13.176 --> 00:30:14.885
Using imaging-based studies,

554
00:30:15.716 --> 00:30:19.216
several groups have shown a remodeling of the bone marrow

555
00:30:19.276 --> 00:30:22.796
niche in murine models, and this includes

556
00:30:22.856 --> 00:30:24.506
increased ECM deposition,

557
00:30:25.356 --> 00:30:29.240
loss in the integrity of blood vessels.And as well

558
00:30:29.320 --> 00:30:32.090
as neuropathies in some cases,

559
00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:36.800
suggesting that the cancer is indeed actively, even in the context of

560
00:30:36.820 --> 00:30:39.900
leukemia, remodeling specifically the bone marrow niche.

561
00:30:42.220 --> 00:30:45.700
In addition to the remodeling itself, what we're interested in is the signals that

562
00:30:45.740 --> 00:30:47.680
can support disease progression.

563
00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:51.820
These can be cell-cell interactions, adhesive interactions,

564
00:30:52.300 --> 00:30:53.720
or secretory factors.

565
00:30:54.900 --> 00:30:58.820
My initial work as a postdoctoral fellow in Tanush Taraya's

566
00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:02.480
lab used candidate-based approaches to look at

567
00:31:02.540 --> 00:31:04.320
cell-cell interactions and adhesion.

568
00:31:04.860 --> 00:31:08.060
And what we found is that CD98 and

569
00:31:08.100 --> 00:31:11.660
tetraspanin-3 mediated adhesion signals can be

570
00:31:11.680 --> 00:31:15.550
important for sustaining the leukemia stem cell populations, as

571
00:31:15.620 --> 00:31:19.160
well as for promoting aggressive disease outcomes.

572
00:31:21.740 --> 00:31:24.340
Moving on from there, we wanted to take a more

573
00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:29.340
higher-level view of the secreted factors that could be coming from the stromal

574
00:31:29.360 --> 00:31:33.300
components. And to do that, we leveraged single-cell RNA

575
00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:33.919
sequencing.

576
00:31:35.800 --> 00:31:39.510
One of the problems in the field of leukemia for long has been that most models

577
00:31:39.620 --> 00:31:43.500
that we have used in the past have required conditioning of the bone marrow

578
00:31:43.920 --> 00:31:47.420
to actually allow the engraftment of the leukemia cells.

579
00:31:48.020 --> 00:31:51.220
But now we have models that can grow in

580
00:31:51.260 --> 00:31:54.040
immunocompetent mice without the need of

581
00:31:54.460 --> 00:31:55.480
niche-destroying

582
00:31:57.440 --> 00:31:59.540
techniques. So we can

583
00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:04.660
take leukemia stem progenitor cells, engraft them in immunocompetent

584
00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:08.600
mice, and then isolate the CD45 negative Ter119

585
00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:12.140
negative bone marrow stromal cells from

586
00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:14.520
these mice at different time points.

587
00:32:14.980 --> 00:32:17.440
The models that we use are very aggressive.

588
00:32:17.860 --> 00:32:21.820
Between two to three weeks is the lifespan of the mice with these cancers, and

589
00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:24.600
these are the time points on the survival curve highlighted here.

590
00:32:25.860 --> 00:32:29.140
So our single-cell sequencing

591
00:32:29.180 --> 00:32:33.120
analysis does identify many populations that are seen in the

592
00:32:33.140 --> 00:32:36.860
normal bone marrow niche. These analyses are leveraging some newer

593
00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:40.860
studies in the last five to six years of the bone marrow microenvironment,

594
00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:43.380
which have developed the pipelines for analyzing these data.

595
00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:47.480
These include the subpopulations of endothelial cells,

596
00:32:48.200 --> 00:32:51.869
multiple different fibroblast populations, which we hope to study in the future,

597
00:32:51.940 --> 00:32:55.490
but we are still understanding how to separate them out and work with them in

598
00:32:55.520 --> 00:32:58.140
vitro. The MSCs, and as well as the

599
00:32:58.200 --> 00:33:00.860
osteo-associated populations.

600
00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:05.900
But interestingly, over time, what we see is that these populations do change.

601
00:33:06.240 --> 00:33:10.200
The cancer is changing the transcriptional profile, which is very obvious

602
00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:13.960
here in the arteriolar endothelial and the mesenchymal cells,

603
00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:18.640
suggesting that the populations are perhaps secreting different factors

604
00:33:18.700 --> 00:33:20.240
or just physically changing.

605
00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:24.760
So a gene expression profiling and pathway analysis

606
00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:28.620
identifies that a downregulation of osteo

607
00:33:28.680 --> 00:33:32.120
lineage differentiation in MSCs, which is perhaps

608
00:33:32.380 --> 00:33:36.320
reminiscent of what happens in people with AML who often present

609
00:33:36.360 --> 00:33:37.240
with osteopenias.

610
00:33:38.520 --> 00:33:42.480
We also see downregulation of adhesion in the

611
00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:46.360
endothelial cells. This would perhaps explain the leaky blood

612
00:33:46.420 --> 00:33:50.320
vessels seen by Dominic Bonnet's group and others using in vivo imaging techniques.

613
00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:55.540
So now moving on to what are the factors that are secreted from these cells,

614
00:33:55.600 --> 00:33:58.280
and how are they actually being used by the cancer?

615
00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:03.110
As you can imagine, there are hundreds or thousands of different factors that

616
00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:06.930
we can identify. How does one go about narrowing down on what is

617
00:34:06.980 --> 00:34:08.940
actually important for the cancer cell growth?

618
00:34:10.440 --> 00:34:14.380
To address that, we switched to the cancer cells perspective and looked

619
00:34:14.440 --> 00:34:18.220
at the cell surface receptors that are being enriched and expressed on the

620
00:34:19.200 --> 00:34:22.261
leukemia cells themselves because they are perhaps the first ones that are going to

621
00:34:22.281 --> 00:34:25.120
be responding to the signals from the niche.

622
00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:30.020
So to this end, we carried out an RNA-seq analysis

623
00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:34.361
from healthy donor bone marrow C34-positive cells,

624
00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:36.000
as well as

625
00:34:37.020 --> 00:34:40.160
patient samples from two different models of aggressive leukemia, acute myeloid

626
00:34:40.180 --> 00:34:43.720
leukemia, as well as the blast crisis phase of chronic myeloid

627
00:34:43.740 --> 00:34:47.629
leukemia. They are pathophysiologically very similar diseases, and

628
00:34:47.680 --> 00:34:49.600
at their most aggressive phases, they are

629
00:34:51.200 --> 00:34:52.801
often treated similarly in the clinic.

630
00:34:53.460 --> 00:34:57.020
And this work was done in collaboration with Craig Jordan in

631
00:34:57.060 --> 00:34:57.480
Colorado.

632
00:34:58.880 --> 00:35:02.370
What we find now from here is differentially expressed genes,

633
00:35:02.840 --> 00:35:04.140
which we can then

634
00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:09.700
cross to publicly available cell surface atlases to narrow

635
00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:13.640
down on the cell surface proteins, as well as a genome-wide in

636
00:35:14.060 --> 00:35:17.200
vivo CRISPR screen that we did, which has identified

637
00:35:17.340 --> 00:35:19.980
dependencies of the leukemia cells in vivo.

638
00:35:20.690 --> 00:35:24.300
And we can now identify signals that are unique to AML,

639
00:35:24.720 --> 00:35:28.020
to BCCML, or both, and then use tools like

640
00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:32.500
NicheNet to develop these maps, which can now show

641
00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:36.460
crosstalk between receptors on the leukemia cells and the ligands

642
00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:40.500
being secreted or signals coming from the different stromal

643
00:35:40.509 --> 00:35:44.360
populations. While we did not do the immune niche ourselves, we

644
00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:48.120
were able to leverage data from patient AML immune

645
00:35:48.180 --> 00:35:51.840
microenvironment from Janis Ifantidis' group, which was very

646
00:35:51.900 --> 00:35:52.260
helpful.

647
00:35:54.020 --> 00:35:57.620
These kind of maps did identify interactions that have previously been

648
00:35:57.660 --> 00:36:00.380
reported in literature validating our approach in

649
00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:04.310
principle. And the two that I'm going to talk about today

650
00:36:04.360 --> 00:36:08.060
are the SLC66A6 and LDLR, primarily

651
00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:12.020
because those were the ones which were strongly associated with poor prognosis in

652
00:36:12.080 --> 00:36:14.180
patient samples in DCGA data.

653
00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:19.250
So starting with SLC66A6, it is the taurine transporter.

654
00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:25.280
Taurine itself is a non-essential amino acid, which

655
00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:29.440
can be obtained by diet, is also synthesized by the liver,

656
00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:33.472
primarily from cysteine.And what we found, which was very

657
00:36:33.492 --> 00:36:37.352
interesting, was that the expression of CDO1

658
00:36:37.412 --> 00:36:41.202
was unique, was one, was shocking to see it was present in the bone marrow, and

659
00:36:41.332 --> 00:36:44.502
second, it was uniquely restricted to the osteolineage cells,

660
00:36:44.952 --> 00:36:48.632
suggesting that these perhaps could be a local source of taurine in the bone marrow

661
00:36:48.692 --> 00:36:48.952
niche.

662
00:36:49.772 --> 00:36:53.552
So our in vitro experiments where we take MSCs and

663
00:36:53.592 --> 00:36:57.482
induce osteogenic differentiation, what we see is that they do indeed secrete

664
00:36:57.482 --> 00:37:00.762
taurine in the media as soon as we induce osteogenic differentiation.

665
00:37:02.272 --> 00:37:06.102
Consistent with this, there's increased taurine in the bone marrow plasma of

666
00:37:06.132 --> 00:37:09.092
mice with leukemia compared to the ones which don't have cancer.

667
00:37:10.992 --> 00:37:14.212
Before doing any functional studies, we wanted to ensure that this was not

668
00:37:14.252 --> 00:37:17.192
something which was restricted or unique to the mouse bone marrow niche.

669
00:37:17.792 --> 00:37:21.272
So we collaborated with our physician colleagues to get patient samples,

670
00:37:21.692 --> 00:37:24.512
biopsies from patients who have progressive disease,

671
00:37:26.072 --> 00:37:29.152
like MDS to AML, and then from AML diagnosis to

672
00:37:29.192 --> 00:37:33.112
relapse. And in most cases, we do

673
00:37:33.192 --> 00:37:36.642
see a striking increase in the synthesis of CDO1

674
00:37:36.672 --> 00:37:39.862
in the patient as the disease progresses in patients,

675
00:37:40.162 --> 00:37:43.872
suggesting that this is perhaps a signal that is conserved between

676
00:37:43.912 --> 00:37:44.912
mice and human.

677
00:37:46.232 --> 00:37:48.902
To functionally test the requirement of

678
00:37:48.932 --> 00:37:52.732
taurine being produced by the stromal cells, we

679
00:37:52.792 --> 00:37:55.292
use in vitro co-culture assays. We can do these with mice.

680
00:37:55.392 --> 00:37:57.252
I'm going to show you data which we have done with human.

681
00:37:57.852 --> 00:38:01.712
So we established mesenchymal stromal cell cultures from bone marrow

682
00:38:01.772 --> 00:38:02.352
of patients,

683
00:38:03.732 --> 00:38:07.282
transduced them with shRNAs targeting either control or CDO1,

684
00:38:08.052 --> 00:38:12.032
and after promoting differentiation, we add leukemia cells now from

685
00:38:12.072 --> 00:38:15.812
the peripheral blood of the same patient and look at the support and

686
00:38:15.932 --> 00:38:17.392
growth of these cells over time.

687
00:38:18.412 --> 00:38:22.132
And what you can see here is that cells that are growing in an environment, an

688
00:38:22.192 --> 00:38:26.112
MSC osteolineage environment that does not express CDO are not able to

689
00:38:26.152 --> 00:38:30.032
survive well, and neither are they able to form colonies, suggesting

690
00:38:30.052 --> 00:38:33.552
that this taurine from the local niche is perhaps playing a functional role in

691
00:38:33.592 --> 00:38:35.052
supporting the leukemia cells.

692
00:38:37.072 --> 00:38:40.552
So taurine in the bone marrow is perhaps a very small source.

693
00:38:41.092 --> 00:38:44.772
Much of it is diet or liver. So we wanted to see in vivo

694
00:38:44.912 --> 00:38:48.892
whether inhibiting taurine synthesis in the MSCs or the

695
00:38:48.912 --> 00:38:52.712
osteolineage cells could actually have any impact at all on disease progression.

696
00:38:53.552 --> 00:38:57.272
So to do that, we developed a CDO1 floxed mouse, crossed it to the

697
00:38:57.412 --> 00:39:01.392
MSC specific Prx1-Cre, and used these mice as

698
00:39:01.452 --> 00:39:02.712
recipients of leukemia.

699
00:39:03.892 --> 00:39:07.652
As you can see here, we do indeed see that inhibiting CDO1

700
00:39:07.692 --> 00:39:11.052
expression in MSC lineage specifically can

701
00:39:11.212 --> 00:39:14.432
improve survival outcomes, at least in part,

702
00:39:14.992 --> 00:39:18.712
suggesting that the locally produced taurine is perhaps indeed playing a role in

703
00:39:18.722 --> 00:39:19.592
disease progression.

704
00:39:21.332 --> 00:39:25.052
I'm going to switch gears and now talk about the transporter

705
00:39:25.112 --> 00:39:28.832
itself and its function in promoting disease growth.

706
00:39:29.652 --> 00:39:33.492
So what I did not mention before is that we do not see CDO1

707
00:39:33.512 --> 00:39:35.132
expression in the leukemia cells themselves.

708
00:39:35.952 --> 00:39:38.372
There's barely any RNA expressed, so they're

709
00:39:38.672 --> 00:39:41.852
primarily relying on taurine coming from outside.

710
00:39:43.192 --> 00:39:43.372
We

711
00:39:44.452 --> 00:39:48.172
obtained a taurine transporter knockout mouse from a collaborator in Japan and

712
00:39:48.192 --> 00:39:50.232
used these now to model cancers

713
00:39:51.392 --> 00:39:53.052
using multiple different oncogenes.

714
00:39:53.792 --> 00:39:57.032
And in every case that we tested, we see that

715
00:39:57.732 --> 00:40:01.352
the genetic loss of the taurine transporter can improve survival outcomes

716
00:40:01.372 --> 00:40:02.842
dramatically in many cases,

717
00:40:04.232 --> 00:40:07.052
suggesting that inhibiting this gene may be of value.

718
00:40:07.072 --> 00:40:11.052
But to actually test if this was the case in patient samples, we used

719
00:40:11.172 --> 00:40:15.132
shRNA-based approaches. So we get primary human patient AML

720
00:40:15.172 --> 00:40:18.432
samples or donor-derived human

721
00:40:18.572 --> 00:40:22.332
HSPCs, transduce them with shRNAs

722
00:40:22.392 --> 00:40:25.462
now targeting the taurine transporter, and

723
00:40:26.412 --> 00:40:29.052
look at their growth in vivo in immunodeficient mice.

724
00:40:30.612 --> 00:40:33.952
Now, this is data from multiple different samples. There's huge heterogeneity.

725
00:40:33.992 --> 00:40:37.752
These samples really are not always engraftable, and even when they do,

726
00:40:37.822 --> 00:40:40.952
there's heterogeneity in the way they do it because they're primary samples.

727
00:40:41.932 --> 00:40:45.832
But despite that, we do see a strong impact on the growth

728
00:40:45.932 --> 00:40:49.892
of the leukemia cells when their expression of

729
00:40:49.932 --> 00:40:51.212
the taurine transporter is knocked down.

730
00:40:52.472 --> 00:40:56.372
However, this is not the case in the normal 34 positive cells,

731
00:40:56.872 --> 00:41:00.532
suggesting that there may be a therapeutic window for targeting

732
00:41:00.612 --> 00:41:04.332
this particular transporter in this disease.

733
00:41:05.252 --> 00:41:07.872
But which subtype would one want to target it in?

734
00:41:10.792 --> 00:41:14.672
Just looking at expression, we don't really see preferential expression based on

735
00:41:14.692 --> 00:41:17.092
mutation profile in the patient data sets.

736
00:41:17.802 --> 00:41:21.512
But what we do see is that high expression is linked

737
00:41:21.612 --> 00:41:25.292
to venetoclax resistance. So venetoclax has recently become

738
00:41:25.952 --> 00:41:29.432
